Is that possible to enable `USE_DIST_KVSTORE=1` by default in the official docker image and the pip packages? @pineking 

This could really help for anyone who wants to try MXNet.
be using a BucketingModule to define your symbol model when you use your custom BucketIter
I see that error message in CI sometimes. Are you sure this is the reason the deployment failed?
The op.h file is auto-generated. Did you set USE_CPP_PACKAGE=1 in config.mk?

All necessary information for resolving your issue has been provided to you in the above thread, and BucketingModule has been repeatedly mentioned in the above locked thread.

I closed the above issue because you're asking others to debug your code, while not being willing to look at API doc. This is disrespectful to other people's time.

I locked the conversation because you were disrespectful to me who helped you on this issue.

I think this kind of behavior is harmful to the community and must be discouraged. I assure you that the same treatment will be applied if such behavior persists.
@arank Do you know if anything on Jetson could cause this?
I think dist-kvstore is enabled in pip. ping @szha for further confirmation

@janelu9 [a quick search](https://github.com/apache/incubator-mxnet/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue%20author%3Ajanelu9%20) turns up that all your issues are similar to this one, and all of them don't follow the issue templates and always lacks the necessary details. Not only does this cost other people a lot of time to go back and forth with you, you're unlikely to receive the help you need either. Next time when you open issues, please be considerate and provide all the necessary information following the issue template.
@tobegit3hub yes, all pip variants starting from 0.11.1 (currently only in nightly pre-releases) are built with ps-lite now.

I found that, from dmlc-core/tracker/dmlc_tracker/ssh.py, one compute node should hold both one worker and one server. I am not sure whether this is correct?
However, my task management system launch a process on one node exclusively. So, one server and one worker are located on two nodes.
I wonder whether this is the problem, and I will try to fix it.

\------

I successfully made one worker and one server on one node, however, the problem is not solved. The accuracy is still about 0.1 after many batches.
1394 error is usually a false issue that's caused by importing an opencv that was built with 1394 I/O, and it doesn't cause real harm.
Closing this issue due to inactivity for now.

```
- arange *** FAILED ***
  1.14497025E-5 was not less than or equal to 1.0E-5 (NDArraySuite.scala:173)
```
FYI: The reason of test failure looks not related.
@oza True, I wonder if some one has introduced again new failure :-|
The reason of test failure looks to be related to #8087. Please don't commit this before passing all tests.
Added a pull request to fix that  flaky test. https://github.com/apache/incubator-mxnet/pull/8095
@javelinjs
@joey2014 It still has the error information: ImportError: You used to compile with protoc --python_out=./ ./caffe.proto

this is giving a CUDA error so it is probably isn't finding your CUDA install or the version of CUDA you installed and mxnet expects is off. Did you go through the Jetpac setup to get the CUDA/CUDNN drivers onto the machine? What version of CUDA/CUDNN do you have?

@formath There's the case that `len(shared_group.execs) > len(self._context)`, which should also be valid. So we need to change the assertion to `len(shared_group.execs) >= len(self._context)`.

I got mxnet with python installed on Windows 10 with pip using Anaconda 2. Seems to work with VS2017, although Anaconda2 has to be installed with the VS2017 installer. Thank you for the tips! 

Would be good if using pip install for Windows is reference on the installation webpage of mxnet.io . Really saves tons of work.
